    "boxscore_url": "https://www.charlotte49ers.com/sports/baseball/stats/2026/st-john-s/boxscore/19752",
    "recap_url": "https://www.charlotte49ers.com/news/2026/3/13/baseball-charlottes-rally-comes-up-short-against-st-john-s",
    "recap_headline": "Charlotte",
    "recap_text": "CHARLOTTE \u2013\nCharlotte Baseball scored four runs in the bottom of the eighth inning to pull within two, but couldn't complete the comeback in the ninth in an 8-6 loss to St. John's on Friday evening (March 13) at Hayes Stadium.\nTrailing by six entering the home half of the eighth, Charlotte (12-5) plated four runs from three hits, including a pinch-hit, RBI-single from\nJohnny Sutryk\n, but couldn't keep the rally going in the ninth in the loss to the Red Storm (6-11).\nSutryk's hit was his first of the season and one of 10 in the game for the 49ers, their fifth consecutive game and 12th time overall this season recording double-digit hits.\nSpencer Nolan\nhad a pair of knocks in the game for his team-leading 10th multi-hit game of the year, as did\nTodd Hudson\nand\nAdrian Jimenez\n.\nDawson Bryce\nkept his hitting streak alive at 11 straight games after picking up a hit, while\nCody Gunderson\nand\nAlec DeMartino\neach had a hit as well.\nHudson also scored twice and drove in a pair of runs, with Nolan responsible for bringing home a pair as well.\nEddie Copper\nstarted the game on the mound and was saddled with the loss, giving up five runs in the first six innings while striking out six.\nAdam Stanton\npicked up a strikeout in one inning of work while\nSebastian Perez\nand\nAJ Camp\ncombined to pitch the final two frames.\nHOW IT HAPPENED\nCopper got through the St. John's lineup with no trouble the first time around, sitting the side down in order in each of the first three innings.\nHowever, the Red Storm opened the scoring in the fourth, despite not recording a hit. A hit batter started the inning and then moved up to second on a groundout. He then stole third and came home on a sac fly to the warning track in deep center field. Another runner was on base for the sac fly and moved up to third on the play, but he was left there when Copper registered his fourth K of the day to end the inning.\nCharlotte had a prime opportunity to tie the score up in the bottom of the frame with a pair of hits and a hit batter. Gunderson singled to centerfield with two gone before\nDylan Koontz\nwas hit by a pitch to put a pair on. DeMartino was the next batter up and poked one through the right side, but Gunderson was thrown out at the plate and CLT came up empty.\nThe Niner faithful didn't have to wait long for the home team to level the score as Charlotte tied things up in the fifth with a little bit of small-ball and some timely hitting. Hudson drew a walk to get the inning started before back-to-back sacrifice bunt attempts by Jimenez and\nCale Stricklin\n. They were both successful in getting the bunts down, but an error by the St. John's pitcher allowed Jimenez to reach safely on the sacrifice, meaning Stricklin's bunt put a pair in scoring position.\nNolan was the next batter and bounced one deep enough to the hole at short to plate Hudson from third and reach base safely with a hit. Jimenez moved up to third on the RBI-single, putting runners on the corners with one out, but the Red Storm fired consecutive strikeouts to leave the go-ahead run standing 90 feet away.\nIt didn't stay tied for long, as St. John's opened it up with four runs in the sixth. A double with a pair of runners on brought the first two runs of the inning across and then a home run on the very next pitch scored the other two.\nCharlotte got one of the runs back in the bottom of the frame when DeMartino came home on a single from Hudson. A two-base error put DeMartino in scoring position and he crossed the plate two pitches later when Hudson found the grass in center field.\nThe Red Storm put another crooked number on the board in the eighth inning, hitting a three-run homer to push their lead up to six, 8-2.\nThe Niners mounted a comeback in the home half of the inning, bringing around four to cut the deficit to two heading into the ninth. Gunderson and Koontz drew back-to-back walks to get the rally started and both moved into scoring position on a wild pitch. A groundout to the right side of the infield from DeMartino brought the first run of the inning home before a double down the line in right by Hudson scored the next one.\nA groundout to the left side moved Hudson to third and a pinch-hit single from Sutryk advanced Hudson the final 90 feet. Sutryk swiped second to get into scoring position, setting up an RBI-single to center from Nolan.\nThat was it for Charlotte's rally in the eighth as a new arm for SJU came in out of the bullpen and got the final out of the frame. The Niners kept it a two-run game through the top of the last but couldn't close the gap anymore, going down in order in the final frame.\nUP NEXT\nThe two sides are back at it again on Saturday afternoon (March 14) with a 4 p.m. game at The Hayes."
  },
